{{Infobox writer | name = Mary Evelyn Hitchcock | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Mary Evelyn Hitchcock.png | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = Mary Doyle | birth_name = Mary Evelyn Higgins | birth_date = March 10, 1849 | birth_place = Virginia | death_date = {{dda|1920|4|6|1849|3|10}} | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = author, traveler | language = | nationality = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[Lawrence Academy at Groton|Lawrence Academy]] | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''Two women in the Klondike: the story of a journey to the gold-fields of Alaska'' | awards = | spouse = Roswell D. Hitchcock, Jr. | relations = | partner = | children = Harriet Bradford Hitchcock Harriman | years_active = | module = | signature = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} --> | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }} '''Mary Evelyn Hitchcock''' ([[pen name]]s, '''Mary Doyle''' and '''Mrs. Roswell D. Hitchcock'''; March 10, 1849 - April 6, 1920) was an American author and explorer. She was part of the Floradora Company in the early 20th century, and also worked from the New York ''World'' as a reporter.{{sfn|Price|1999|p=112}}
==Early life and education== Mary Evelyn Higgins was born in [[Virginia]], March 10, 1849. She was the daughter of Capt. Thomas A. (of [[Norfolk, Virginia]]) and Cecelia (Fitzgerald) Higgins. She was educated at [[Lawrence Academy at Groton|Lawrence Academy]], where she received academic honors.{{sfn|Leonard|Mohr|Holmes|1907|p=676}}
==Career== She married Commander Roswell D. Hitchcock, [[United States Navy|USN]], (son of [[Roswell Dwight Hitchcock]]) and they had one daughter, Harriet Bradford Hitchcock Harriman (1872-1939).{{sfn|Leonard|Mohr|Holmes|1907|p=676}} Hitchcock accompanied her husband to the [[Weltausstellung 1873 Wien|Vienna Exposition, 1873]], [[Exposition Universelle (1878)|Paris Exposition, 1878]], to Japan, 1882, where his ship remained two years; and again in 1892, when he was captain of [[USS Alert (AS-4)|USS ''Alert'']]. After the death of the husband, she made a tour of the world.{{sfn|Leonard|Mohr|Holmes|1907|p=676}} [[File:Two Women in the Klondike 1.png|thumb|Hitchcock and [[Edith Van Buren]] on the ''St. Paul'' with their dogs.]] In 1898, she went to [[Klondike, Yukon|Klondike]] with her friend [[Edith Van Buren]], embarking from [[San Francisco]] on a steamer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mary Hitchcock and Edith Van Buren - Klondike Tourists|url=https://postalmuseum.si.edu/gold/hitchcock.html|website=National Postal Museum}}</ref> Their luggage included multiple pets and an [[History of film|early motion picture device]] called an animatoscope.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bottomore|first1=Stephen|title=Mary Ellen Hitchcock|url=http://www.victorian-cinema.net/hitchcock|website=Who's Who of Victorian Cinema}}</ref> Hitchcock climbed [[Skagway, Alaska|Skagway Pass]] on foot before the days of the railroad. She subsequently wrote the book, ''Two Women in the Klondike'', which described this visit to the Yukon.{{sfn|Leonard|Mohr|Holmes|1907|p=676}}
Hitchcock was so impressed with the mining and agricultural possibilities of the Yukon that she spread the knowledge she had gained through lectures, which added largely to funds for churches and hospitals. She returned to the north, where she staked more than 100 claims and because so deeply interested financially that she spent the greater part of five years there. {{sfn|Leonard|Mohr|Holmes|1907|p=676}}
In 1904, Hitchcock organized and was president of The Entertainment Club, in [[New York City]]. She was also a Fellow of the [[National Geographic Society]], as well as a member of the [[Daughters of the Confederacy]].{{sfn|Leonard|Mohr|Holmes|1907|p=676}}
==''Two women in the Klondike''== [[File:Two Women in the Klondike (1899 cover).png|thumb|''Two Women in the Klondike'' (1899 cover)]] ''Two women in the Klondike: the story of a journey to the gold-fields of Alaska'' (New York, G. P. Putnam's Sons, 1899) describes the adventures of Hitchcock and Edith Van Buren, a grandniece of [[President Van Buren]], during a perilous and eventful journey taken in the summer of 1898. Owing to the waters of the [[Yukon River]] being low, the two women were delayed for some time at [[Dawson City]] where they located miner's claims and lived as squatters. Besides the interesting incidents of travel included, the book included graphic descriptions of the [[Klondike Gold Rush|Klondike]] region, and accounts of local customs and superstitions, as well as mining methods.{{sfn|Leypoldt|1899|p=999}} She died April 6, 1920 and is buried at Oak Grove Cemetery, Fall River, Massachusetts.<ref name="findagrave.com">{{cite web|title=Mary E Higgins Hitchcock (1849 - 1920) - Find A Grave Memorial|url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin//fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=151163474|website=www.findagrave.com|accessdate=18 July 2017}}</ref>
==Selected works== * ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=mpodAAAAMAAJ Two women in the Klondike : the story of a journey to the gold-fields of Alaska]'', 1899 * ''Tales out of school about naval officers (and others) by a woman who has lived on a man-of-war'', 1908 * ''First reader : for use in the first year'', 1912 * ''Second reader : for use in the second year'', 1912 * ''Third reader'', 1912 * ''Standard Catholic readers by grades. Third year'', 1913 * ''Fifth reader : for use in the seventh and eighth years'', 1913 * ''Life was like that'', 1936
